- Do you **support multiple languages** in the same project? **Yes**

pull_request.title: Add observer for progress reporting
pull_request.body:
Introduce a new progress reporting interface using observer pattern, while maintaining backward compatibility with the legacy progress_callback (int percent) API.

## Summary by Sourcery

Add a new progress reporting interface based on the observer pattern that emits rich Progress objects for download, parse, and save steps, while preserving the legacy integerâ€callback API with deprecation warnings and ensuring backward compatibility.

New Features:
- Introduce a structured progress reporting API with Progress and ProgressObserver classes for monitoring long-running operations
- Provide a ProgressStatus enum and decorators to attach step, total_steps, and status metadata to progress events
- Maintain backward compatibility by adapting the legacy integer-based progress_callback and issuing deprecation warnings

Enhancements:
- Extend SpecFactory, IODSpecBuilder, DocHandler (XHTML/PDF), and DOMTableSpecParser to emit Progress objects during downloading, parsing, and model saving
- Add utility functions (add_progress_step, offset_progress_steps) to annotate and adjust progress events
- Update mkdocs to include the new progress API documentation

Tests:
- Add comprehensive tests to verify progress_observer functionality, legacy callback adaptation, and correct event sequences across components

comment.body:
## Step 1: Enable GitHub Pages ### ðŸ“– Theory: What is GitHub Pages? GitHub Pages lets you turn your repository into a website. This is a great way to share your project, resume, portfolio, documentation, or even a blog with the world. When you enable GitHub Pages on a repository, GitHub takes the content that's on the main branch and publishes a website based on its contents. > [!NOTE] > Learn more in the [GitHub Pages documentation](https://docs.github.com/en/pages/getting-started-with-github-pages/about-github-pages). ### âŒ¨ï¸ Activity: Enable GitHub Pages 1. Open this repository in a new browser tab so you can work on the steps while you read the instructions in this tab. 1. Under your repository name, click **Settings**. 1. Click **Pages** in the **Code and automation** section. 1. Ensure **Deploy from a branch** is selected from the **Source** drop-down menu, and then select `main` from the **Branch** drop-down menu. 1. Click the **Save** button. 1. With GitHub Pages enabled Mona will be preparing the next step in this exercise!
Having trouble? ðŸ¤·
- Turning on GitHub Pages creates a deployment of your repository. GitHub Actions may take up to a minute to respond while waiting for the deployment. Future steps will be about 20 seconds; this step is slower.
